# GitHub push offer (ongoing — child projects from Project Starter Pack)

After **meaningful** work (a feature, fix, or when the user says **done** / **finished** / **end of session**), and **`git remote get-url origin`** succeeds:

- End with **one short line** offering to update GitHub, e.g.  
  > **GitHub:** say if you want me to **commit and push**, **commit only** (local), or **skip for now**.

**Before offering:** run `npm run build` when you changed app code; do not offer push if the build fails unless the user only changed docs.

**If they agree to push:** `git add -A`, commit with a short honest message, `git push` (use their existing branch; do not rename branches unless they ask). If push fails (auth, conflicts), explain and stop — **never** ask for tokens or passwords in chat.

**Do not:**

- Commit or push without the user agreeing in that turn.
- Repeat the offer in the same chat unless there is **new** work or **new** unpushed commits.
- Nag about push if **`origin`** is not configured (GitHub was never linked — off-machine backup is optional; see [docs/INDUSTRY_STANDARD_VERSIONING.md](docs/INDUSTRY_STANDARD_VERSIONING.md)).
- Offer on every tiny edit or mid-task unless they asked.

**First-time GitHub link** uses [github-setup-offer.mdc](github-setup-offer.mdc) and [docs/GITHUB_SETUP_WALKTHROUGH.md](docs/GITHUB_SETUP_WALKTHROUGH.md) — not this rule.
